{"timestamp":"2026-03-26T20:10:04.975Z","intent":"Quality Manager dashboard for a health system. The user monitors AI agent escalations to help close care gaps and tracks progress against quality benchmarks/goals (e.g. HEDIS measures). The surface has four regions: (1) Summary KPI bar — care gap closure rate, escalation count, overdue escalations, benchmark attainment %; (2) Escalation queue — list of AI-flagged patients needing human review, with measure name, patient, risk level, days open, and action to resolve or reassign; (3) Benchmark/goal tracker — per-measure progress bars showing current rate vs target (e.g. Colorectal Screening 72% of 80% goal); (4) Recent activity feed — log of closed gaps and resolved escalations. Actions: resolve escalation, reassign, drill into patient, export report.","scope":"surface","domain":"care-gaps","build_mode":"block-composition","selected_blocks":["SectionHeader","StatCard","ActionableRow","Progress","ActivityLogRow","Button","Card","DataTable","Alert"],"confidence":0.87}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-26T20:19:23.089Z","intent":"Quality management solution for health systems. Quality managers need to: (1) oversee escalations from AI agents — when AI flags a care gap or clinical concern it escalates to a human quality manager for review and action; (2) monitor progress toward closure of care gaps across a patient population. The surface includes: an escalation inbox/queue showing AI-generated escalations with patient context, priority, reason, and action buttons (Accept, Reassign, Dismiss); a care gap dashboard showing open/closed/in-progress gaps by measure type (e.g. HbA1c, mammogram, colorectal screening) with trend charts and drill-down; a detail panel for individual patients showing their specific gaps, escalation history, assigned care coordinators, and closure status. Users are admin-level quality managers, not bedside clinicians.","scope":"surface","domain":"care-gaps","build_mode":"block-composition","selected_blocks":["EntityContextHeader","SectionHeader","Tabs","ActionableRow","AlertBanner","StatCard","Chart","DataTable","Badge","Button","DropdownMenu","Skeleton","Alert"],"confidence":0.82}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-26T21:21:30.550Z","intent":"Quality management workflow: when a care coordinator clicks \"Review\" on an escalation in the QualityView, it opens a new AI chat session in the left-side chat panel (AIChatPanel). The new session appears at the top of the \"Recents\" list in the NavSidebar with the patient name + measure as its title. The chat session is pre-seeded with an AI briefing message that summarises the escalation (patient identity, priority, measure, detail, open care gaps for that patient) and offers three quick-action chips: \"Schedule outreach call\", \"Reassign to care coordinator\", \"Mark as reviewed\". The session persists in the recents list. Coordinators can then type free-form follow-up questions. This involves: (1) a Session data model lifted to App.tsx, (2) NavSidebar recents becoming dynamic, (3) AIChatPanel accepting an active session with pre-seeded messages, (4) QualityView calling onOpenEscalationSession(escalation, careGaps) instead of the existing dialog.","scope":"surface","domain":"care-gaps","build_mode":"block-composition","selected_blocks":["EntityContextHeader","SectionHeader","ActionableRow","ChatQuickActionChip","InlineEntityCard","Alert","Skeleton"],"confidence":0.78}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-26T23:37:37.917Z","intent":"An inline \"Schedule Outreach Call\" workflow card embedded directly inside a chat session panel's message list — not a modal or drawer. Used by care coordinators to schedule a follow-up outreach call with a patient from within an active conversation thread.\n\nThe card appears inline in the message list as a structured workflow block. It must support:\n\n1. FORM STATE (pending): A compact card showing:\n   - A date picker (for selecting the call date)\n   - A time picker (for selecting the call time)\n   - A free-text notes field (optional, multi-line, e.g. \"Remind patient about medication refill\")\n   - Two action buttons: \"Confirm Call\" (primary) and \"Cancel\" (ghost/secondary)\n\n2. CONFIRMED STATE: After submission, the card transitions to a read-only confirmed state showing:\n   - A success/confirmed visual indicator\n   - The scheduled date and time\n   - The notes (if provided)\n   - A label like \"Call Scheduled\" with coordinator name and timestamp\n\n3. CANCELLED STATE: If cancelled, the card collapses or shows a muted \"Cancelled\" state inline.\n\nQuestions for the design system:\n- What block composition pattern should be used for an inline workflow card embedded in a message list?\n- What is the correct form layout for date + time + notes in a compact card context?\n- How should state transitions (pending → confirmed, pending → cancelled) be handled — CSS classes, conditional rendering, animation tokens?\n- Are there any safety constraints specific to scheduling UI in a clinical context (e.g., minimum lead time warnings, confirmation requirements, audit trail indicators)?\n- Should the card use a distinct visual container (border, background tint) to differentiate it from regular chat messages?","scope":"block","domain":"forms","build_mode":"block-composition","selected_blocks":[],"confidence":0}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-26T23:47:50.989Z","intent":"Ambient scribing workflow that activates inside the AI chat panel after a coordinator confirms an outreach call. The workflow is an inline card embedded in the session message list (not a modal). States: (1) active-call — live recording indicator with pulsing red dot, elapsed call timer counting up, patient name + MRN displayed, \"End Call\" button; (2) transcribing — shows a live scrolling transcript as lines appear one by one with speaker labels (Coordinator / Patient), still shows elapsed time; (3) summarizing — brief loading state while AI generates the summary; (4) complete — post-call summary card with: SOAP-style structured sections (Subjective, Objective, Assessment, Plan), action items list (follow-up tasks auto-extracted), next steps, and a \"Save to Chart\" button. Coordinator-facing. Safety constraints for clinical call documentation are required.","scope":"block","domain":"clinical-alerts","build_mode":"block-composition","selected_blocks":["Card","Badge","Button","Alert","Separator","Skeleton","Avatar"],"confidence":0.78}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-27T01:17:37.747Z","intent":"Structured notification card in the AI chat panel for a Medication Review task. The card shows: patient name + urgent/routine badge, count of active medications and flagged issues, up to 3 flag summary lines (interaction/PIM/adherence with drug names and severity), a primary \"Review Medications\" button that opens a canvas tab, and a \"Snooze 2h\" secondary button (routine priority only). Has loading, error, and confirmed (post-submission) states. Urgent cards suppress the snooze option and use an urgent badge in the header.","scope":"block","domain":"clinical-alerts","build_mode":"block-composition","selected_blocks":["Card","Badge","Button","InlineEntityCard","StatCard","Alert","Skeleton"],"confidence":0.82}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-27T01:18:19.843Z","intent":"Full canvas view for Medication Review — a multi-section composed page that opens in a new tab when care manager clicks 'Review Medications'. Contains 5 sections stacked vertically with sticky section headers: (1) Medication Overview — patient identity, active med count, flag breakdown stats (interactions/PIMs/adherence gaps), trigger reason if urgent; (2) Active Medications list — each row shows drug name, dose, prescriber, start date, flag severity badges, floated to top by severity; (3) Flagged Issues — grouped by type (Interactions > PIMs > Adherence), each flag shows severity, drugs, rationale, recommended action, and three actions (Mark Resolved / Escalate to Prescriber / Dismiss with reason); progress indicator shows X of N reviewed; (4) Relevant Labs — grouped by linked medication, shows lab name, value, date, critical badge if critical; (5) Documentation — editable note pre-populated by agent, character count, auto-save indicator, Submit Review button blocked if unreviewed flags remain.","scope":"surface","domain":"clinical-alerts","build_mode":"surface-first","selected_blocks":["EntityContextHeader","SectionHeader","StatCard","Badge","ActionableRow","AlertBanner","Tabs","Progress","Textarea","Button","Card","Separator"],"confidence":0.88}
